<br>
stats matter, but not very much. The player behind means more than all the gear you have.<br>
the first time I replied, I didn't even really read it, I just consider the 6 &quot;stats&quot; when I think of the word stats in relation to EQ.  AC and HP are totally different animals to me, as is ATK... <p><br>
<img src="http://kayleechen.homestead.com/files/celesteasignature.jpg" border="0"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/usirarris.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sir Arris</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Knight of Truth</span><br> <font color=#000033>(6/15/01 12:59:52 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Most important stats for monks and why?</span><hr size=1> <br>
HP has been the mainstay on my monk, because he is so rarely tanking, he doesn't need the AC. Caster NPC's are what tears me up on pulling, and  the AC doesn't do jack about that unfotunately. Once you get good pulling an area, you don't get hit all that much except spells.<br>
<br>
Though as always, it really just depends on the group, where you are, etc. With a strong tank with you pulling may as well go for HP &amp; resists, with AC secondary to that. If the tank is weak or slow at taunting, AC &amp; HP all the way. If you aren't pulling, then throw as much HP on as possible.<br>
<br>
Also, when I say HP, I'm also refering to STA, since it gives much nicer boosts to HP then STR does to dmg output, in my opinion. <p><center>
